# Scenario 06: Secure File Transfer Between Servers (scp)

## Problem
Sensitive data stored on a jump host needed to be transferred to an
app server, since developers lacked direct access to app servers.

## Environment
- Source: jump host, file `/tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg`
- Destination: App Server 2, path `/home/data/`
- Each server has a **different** user account (checked via
  infrastructure details table)

## Solution
```bash
scp /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg steve@stapp02:/home/data/
```

## Key Concept: scp path structure
```
scp [source] [user]@[remote-host]:[destination-path]
```
- If a side (source or destination) is the **machine you're currently
  on**, just use a plain path -- no `user@host:` needed.
- If a side is a **remote machine**, it needs `user@host:` prefix.

## Common Mistakes (from experience)
- `nautilus.txt/gpg` instead of `nautilus.txt.gpg` -- a slash instead
  of a dot turns the filename into a nonexistent directory path.
- Assuming the same username works across every server -- each app
  server had a different user (`tony`, `steve`, `banner` for servers
  1, 2, 3 respectively). Always verify against the infrastructure
  details table before running the command.

## What I Learned
- Server hostnames and numbers (stapp01/02/03) are easy to mistype
  under time pressure -- always double-check against the reference
  table rather than typing from memory.
